% \resumeItem{\textbf{Persona-driven Data Synthesis for LLM post-training} (\textit{2024 -- }): I proposed a novel persona-driven data synthesis methodology to scale synthetic data creation\textsuperscript{\ref{pub:persona}}. To this end, I constructed \textbf{``Persona Hub'' — a collection of 1 billion personas}. By showcasing Persona Hub’s use cases in synthesizing high-quality mathematical and logical reasoning problems, instructions, knowledge-rich texts, game NPCs, and tools (functions) at scale, I demonstrate this methodology is versatile, scalable, flexible, and easy to use. Our tech report, once published on arXiv, garnered \redhl{widespread attention and discussion}. This methodology has been not only extensively used within Tencent for large-scale synthetic data creation, but also been embraced by the community with a number of open-source projects.}

% \resumeItem{\textbf{Data Synthesis for Text-to-Text Generation} (\textit{2017 -- 2020}): I proposed a novel approach called Fluency Boost Learning\textsuperscript{\ref{pub:fluency}} to synthesize high-quality training data for seq2seq error correction. This approach uses a pretrained language model (e.g., either an n-gram LM or a neural LM) as a ``reward'' model to rate synthesized instances based on fluency, allowing us to augment error-corrected sentence pairs to a billion scale, significantly advancing the state-of-the-art (achieving the milestone of human-level performance\textsuperscript{\ref{pub:humangec}} in grammar correction for the first time). This approach was further extended to ``reward'' synthesized samples in various dimensions\textsuperscript{\ref{pub:style}} other than fluency, enabling the large-scale data synthesis for more writing assistance tasks (e.g., for formality and politeness rewriting). Moreover, I'm among the earliest\textsuperscript{\ref{pub:tone}} to use GPT-3.5 to generate synthetic data for model training. The series of data synthesis research results in state-of-the-art writing assistant AI in Microsoft Editor, which, as the most used generative models in Microsoft, provides \textbf{trillions of writing suggestions to M365/Office users a year}.}
% \resumeItemListEnd
% \vspace{0.2cm}\textbf{Low-cost GenAI} \vspace{-0.15cm}
% \resumeItemListStart
% \resumeItem{\textbf{Speculative Decoding} (\textit{2021 -- 2022)}: I am \textbf{the first to propose ``Speculative Decoding''}\textsuperscript{\ref{pub:specdec}} for lossless acceleration of Transformer decoding using the idea of speculative execution, and advocate for attention to this decoding paradigm by claiming ``\textit{it may become the de facto standard for Transformer decoding}'' \textbf{in Mar. 2022}. I propose to introduce an independent model to efficiently draft a number of tokens and verify them in parallel to ensure the generation quality, achieving \redhl{$3\times\sim5\times$ lossless acceleration} for seq2seq tasks like machine translation and  summarization. \textbf{This work is followed by} Google's Speculative Decoding (Nov. 2022; \redhl{8 months later than this work}) and Deepmind's Speculative Sampling (Feb. 2023; \redhl{11 months later than this work}) which adapted this idea to LLMs. Now, Speculative Decoding has become a popular technique to speed up LLM inference, as what I foresaw in my tech report\textsuperscript{\ref{tech:aggressive}} in early 2022. \vspace{0.1cm}  \\ Prior to proposing Speculative Decoding, I proposed Aggressive Decoding\textsuperscript{\ref{pub:aggressive}} in 2021, which is a special case of Speculative Decoding for the tasks where inputs and outputs are highly similar. It regards input tokens as draft tokens and verify them in parallel, largely improving the decoding efficiency without additional cost. This approach has been integrated into ONNX Runtime since December 2021 (v1.10) as the decoding engine for writing assistant generative models (e.g., grammar correction, rephrase and style transfer) in Microsoft Editor. This marks \redhl{the first time} the Speculative Decoding paradigm has been applied on a large scale in product deployment, \redhl{reducing deployment costs by 66\% and resulting in over \$30,000,000 in annual savings.}}
% \resumeItem{\textbf{Efficient Architecture} (\textit{2020 -- 2023)}: I was responsible for deploying the Turng-NLG model into Microsoft Editor for the text predictions feature, conducting research in distillation, model compression, architecture optimization, and parameterization to retain model performance while meeting the low latency requirement (30ms). Some architecture and parameterization innovations\textsuperscript{\ref{pub:edgeformer}} were also applied to the on-device (PC) grammar correction model, achieving zero deployment cost and bringing the state-of-the-art grammar correction model to millions of M365/Office Desktop users. Moreover, my research involved efficient modeling\textsuperscript{\ref{pub:icae}\ref{pub:xrag}} of long context (i.e., working memory compression) in LLMs for products (e.g., Copilot in Word) and practical scenarios (e.g., RAG).}
